                                       </picture>
            </a>
         </div>

         <div class="page_genre_index_hierarchy_item_main_inner">
             <h2><a href="/genre/psychedelia/">Psychedelia</a></h2>
             <p class="page_genre_index_hierarchy_item_description">Umbrella of styles intended to replicate or enhance the altered state of consciousness brought on by the use of psychedelic drugs, originating in the 1960s.</p>

             <a onclick="rymQ( () =&gt; { page.genre_index.onClickExpand(37294); });" class="page_genre_index_hierarchy_item_expand ui_button button_expand">
               <span class="expanded">Hide 
                                          27
                                             subgenres
               </span>               
               <span class="not_expanded">Show 
                                          27
                                             subgenres
               </span>
             </a>

         </div>

      </div>

      <div id="page_genre_index_hierarchy_item_expanded_37294" class="page_genre_index_hierarchy_item_expanded">
          <p class="page_genre_index_hierarchy_item_description_expanded">Umbrella of styles intended to replicate or enhance the altered state of consciousness brought on by the use of psychedelic drugs, originating in the 1960s.</p>

      

         
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/neo-psychedelia/">Neo-Psychedelia</a>
                  <p>Developments in Psychedelia since the early 1980s, building on the drug-inspired styles developed in the 1960s.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/baggy/">Baggy</a>
                  <p>Blends Dance and Funk-based grooves with a laid-back, psychedelic atmosphere; features jangly guitars, looping basslines, four-bar drum patterns, and a hypnotic, carefree feel rooted in the Madchester scene of the late 1980s.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/dream-pop/">Dream Pop</a>
                  <p>Reverberated guitars, effects-laden vocals, and dense productions, creating a psychedelic, spacious, and dreamlike sound.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/hypnagogic-pop/">Hypnagogic Pop</a>
                  <p>21st century style that refracts the pop culture of past decades through surreal, low-fidelity production and emulation of outdated media formats or equipment.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/paisley-underground/">Paisley Underground</a>
                  <p>Emerged in Los Angeles in the early 1980s, featuring the energy of Power Pop and New Wave adorned with retro Psychedelia.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/space-rock-revival/">Space Rock Revival</a>
                  <p>Draws from the aesthetics and atmospheric soundscapes of Space Rock combined with the more minimal, back-to-basics approach of the Post-Punk era.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/psychedelic-folk/">Psychedelic Folk</a>
                  <p>Acoustic forms that capture an atmosphere that is at turns dream-like, 'spaced-out', whimsical, haunting, mystical, and melancholic.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/freak-folk/">Freak Folk</a>
                  <p>Loosely defined 2000s Psychedelic Folk revival closely associated with the New Weird America movement, sometimes also a shorthand for certain leftfield styles of psychedelic and Indie Folk.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/free-folk/">Free Folk</a>
                  <p>Incorporates improvisation, repetition and extended song lengths.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/udigrudi/">Udigrudi</a>
                  <p>Movement that emerged in the Brazilian city of Recife during the 1970s that combines psychedelic elements with music of Northeastern Brazil.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/wyrd-folk/">Wyrd Folk</a>
                  <p>Closely tied to mysticism, old folk beliefs, and Folk Horror; often described as 'witchy' or 'pagan.'</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/psychedelic-pop/">Psychedelic Pop</a>
                  <p>Combines unconventional instrumentation with studio effects to create a psychedelic atmosphere within melodic Pop music.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/psychedelic-rock/">Psychedelic Rock</a>
                  <p>Often attempts to emulate or enhance the effects of psychedelic drugs, typically through a variety of instrumental and studio effects or eclectic influences.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/acid-rock/">Acid Rock</a>
                  <p>Loosely defined term often synonymous with Psychedelic Rock; sometimes also used for certain less commercial, more improvisational, or heavier styles.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/freakbeat/">Freakbeat</a>
                  <p>Outgrowth of the Mod movement which combines elements of British Rhythm &amp; Blues and Beat with studio effects common in Psychedelia such as fuzztones, flanging and chorus; often seen as a British relative of the American Garage Psych scene.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/garage-psych/">Garage Psych</a>
                  <p>Emerged from mid-1960s US Garage Rock; characterised by fuzz guitars, cheap organs, experimentation with psychedelic effects and surreal lyricism, and a retained emphasis on raw energy and the pop song format.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/heavy-psych/">Heavy Psych</a>
                  <p>Influenced by Blues Rock's heavy dependence on riffs and improvisatory leanings; features thick, fuzzy guitars, usually slow-to-mid tempos, and extended soloing sections.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/raga-rock/">Raga Rock</a>
                  <p>Influenced by South Asian Music, featuring a droning compositional quality and commonly incorporating instruments like sitar, tambura, and tablas.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/space-rock/">Space Rock</a>
                  <p>Heavy use of synthesizers and guitar effects to create dense atmospheric soundscapes intended to evoke images of outer space and science fiction scenarios.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/space-rock-revival/">Space Rock Revival</a>
                  <p>Draws from the aesthetics and atmospheric soundscapes of Space Rock combined with the more minimal, back-to-basics approach of the Post-Punk era.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/xian-psych/">Xian Psych</a>
                  <p>Portrays Christian and biblical themes through a surreal, transcendent atmosphere, occasionally drawing influence from Christian Liturgical Music.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/zamrock/">Zamrock</a>
                  <p>Developed in the Copperbelt region of Zambia in the 1970s, characterized by its blend of local sounds with influence from Funk, Hard Rock, and Blues Rock.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/psychedelic-soul/">Psychedelic Soul</a>
                  <p>Soul which incorporates the effects and instrumentation of Psychedelic Rock.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/psychsploitation/">Psychsploitation</a>
                  <p>Short-lived genre seeking to capitalise on the popularity of Psychedelia in the 1960s, featuring quickly and cheaply recorded material played by session musicians and put out by budget labels.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/sitarsploitation/">Sitarsploitation</a>
                  <p>Variant of Exotica capitalising on the surge of Western interest in Indian music in the late 1960s; featured melodies played on the sitar (or instruments imitating it) atop Easy Listening accompaniment.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/stoner-metal/">Stoner Metal</a>
                  <p>Combines elements of Doom Metal with elements of Psychedelic Rock and Blues Rock to create a melodic yet heavy sound.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/stoner-rock/">Stoner Rock</a>
                  <p>Psychedelic timbres, raw production, and stylistic influence from Doom Metal and Heavy Psych.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/tropicalia/">Tropicália</a>
                  <p>Blends Brazilian popular styles with the influence of Anglo-American Psychedelia; emerged as part of Brazil's late-1960s counterculture.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
</div>

   </li>

   <li id="page_genre_index_hierarchy_item_38713" class="page_genre_index_hierarchy_item anchor" data-loading="true">



      <div class="page_genre_index_hierarchy_item_main">

         <div class="page_genre_index_hierarchy_item_collage">
