                  <p>Versatile vocal form featuring fast tempos and Frevo de rua instrumentation.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/frevo-de-bloco/">Frevo de bloco</a>
                  <p>Slow, nostalgic form, meant to be sung by women’s choruses accompanied by orchestras featuring strings besides the usual brasses and reeds.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/frevo-de-rua/">Frevo de rua</a>
                  <p>Earliest form, purely instrumental, fast-paced, and meant to be danced in the streets.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/frevo-eletrico/">Frevo elétrico</a>
                  <p>Melodies are led by an electric guitar, instead of large groups featuring brasses and reeds; developed in Salvador, Bahia, during the 1950s</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/manguebeat/">Manguebeat</a>
                  <p>Counterculture fusion of traditional Northeastern Brazilian Music genres with modern Rock and Hip Hop.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
