               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/bronx-drill/">Bronx Drill</a>
                  <p>Bronx scene that popularized Sample Drill and aggressive New York Drill delivery and production in the early 2020s.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/brooklyn-drill/">Brooklyn Drill</a>
                  <p>Brooklyn scene that kickstarted New York Drill in the mid-2010s, primarily through adopted UK Drill production.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/dmv-hip-hop/">DMV Hip Hop</a>
                  <p>Hip Hop from artists in the Greater Washington metropolitan area, including the District of Columbia, southern Maryland, and northern Virginia.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/emo-revival/">Emo Revival</a>
                  <p>Movement beginning in the late 2000s inspired by the styles of 1990s Midwest Emo, often associated with Math Rock-inflected "twinkly" style.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/english-underground/">English Underground</a>
                  <p>Countercultural scene in the United Kingdom, centred around London clubs like UFO and Middle Earth, which peaked in 1966 and 1967.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/ladbroke-grove-scene/">Ladbroke Grove Scene</a>
                  <p>English Underground scene which blossomed in Ladbroke Grove, London, soon after the closure of the popular West End psychedelic club Middle Earth in 1968; faded by the mid-'70s, especially following the rise of Pub Rock and Punk.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/epadunk/">Epadunk</a>
                  <p>Swedish party-oriented scene emerging in the early 2020s, featuring Electronic Dance Music-leaning sound and vulgar lyrics.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/filk/">Filk</a>
                  <p>Broad fandom movement that emerged from Science Fiction conventions in the 1950s focused on original lyrics about fan interests set to popular melodies and original compositions across an eclectic range of genres.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/first-wave-of-detroit-techno/">First Wave of Detroit Techno</a>
                  <p>Influential 1980s scene that invented Detroit Techno and was active in Electro, House, and Synthpop.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/florida-fast-music/">Florida Fast Music</a>
                  <p>DJing and production technique originally developed in South Florida, that primarily involves speeding up Hip Hop, Contemporary R&amp;B, and East Coast Club records.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/fort-thunder-scene/">Fort Thunder Scene</a>
                  <p>Late '90s – early 2000s Noise and Noise Rock scene that formed around an art commune in Providence, Rhode Island.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/franco-flemish-school/">Franco-Flemish School</a>
                  <p>Musical movement centered in the Low Countries, known for its intricate polyphony, emotional expression, and influence on European sacred and secular music from the 1440s to 1550.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/frapcore/">Frapcore</a>
                  <p>Emerged in France in the mid-2010s, uses French rapping with 4-on-the-floor Hardcore [EDM] and especially Gabber instrumentals.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/free-noise/">Free Noise</a>
                  <p>1990s New Zealand scene consisting of Rock-based groups with a focus on Free Improvisation, Drone, and Noise music.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/french-hip-hop/">French Hip Hop</a>
                  <p>Hip Hop originating from France, typically performed in the French language.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/friese-bries/">Friese bries</a>
                  <p>New Wave and Punk inspired music scene located in the province of Friesland in the Netherlands in the mid-1980s.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/furry-music/">Furry Music</a>
                  <p>Created by and for the furry fandom/subculture, an independent art movement focused on anthropomorphic characters.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/futurism/">Futurism</a>
                  <p>Radical and militant attitude, rejection of Western Classical Music and traditional criteria of craft, non-conformity, and a fascination with machines.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/gothenburg-sound/">Gothenburg Sound</a>
                  <p>Pioneering Melodic Death Metal style and scene of Gothenburg, Sweden.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/grebo/">Grebo</a>
                  <p>Short-lived English subculture and associated music; raw, futuristic, sample-heavy form of Alternative Dance with a dirty guitar sound.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/greenwich-village-scene/">Greenwich Village Scene</a>
                  <p>Collective of folk singers who mainly performed in small venues (basements, bars, and coffee houses) throughout Greenwich Village from the late 1950s to mid-1960s.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/group-sounds/">Group Sounds</a>
                  <p>Japanese bands in the mid-to-late 1960s who began performing a style of Beat primarily in English.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/hamburger-schule/">Hamburger Schule</a>
                  <p>Combines traditions of the Neue Deutsche Welle based on Grunge with Pop hooks and elements of Punk Rock.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/harlem-renaissance/">Harlem Renaissance</a>
                  <p>Influential 1920s and '30s cultural movement centered on the African American community in Harlem, New York.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/hellenic-black-metal/">Hellenic Black Metal</a>
                  <p>Black metal scene in Greece with more mid-tempo songwriting and pronounced Heavy Metal influence.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/high-quality-rip/">High Quality Rip</a>
                  <p>Community based on bait-and-switch remixes of music, localized online.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/hipco/">Hipco</a>
                  <p>Developed in Liberia, often featuring conscious and political lyrics and influences from local dance styles.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/hip-hopolo/">Hip-hopolo</a>
                  <p>2000s Polish Hip Hop scene focused on a mainstream approach; received massive popularity and overwhelming criticism from the hip hop community.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/hoboken-sound/">Hoboken Sound</a>
                  <p>Predominantly 1980s New Jersey scene that blended contemporary Post-Punk and New Wave with Power Pop melodicism and Garage Rock directness, becoming heavily influential to early American Jangle Pop and Alternative Rock as a whole.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/holy-terror/">Holy Terror</a>
                  <p>Offshoot of the Process Church of Final Judgement and The Abraxas Foundation sects, focused on the occult and demonology, as well as apocalyptic, misanthropic themes.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/hưng-ca/">Hưng ca</a>
                  <p>Diasporic Vietnamese movement originating in the United States during the 1980s; characterised by nationalistic and socio-political lyrics.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/indie-sleaze-revival/">Indie Sleaze Revival</a>
                  <p>Subcultural movement from the 2020s which appropriates various Dance styles and party-centric aesthetics found within the Bloghouse era from the mid-to-late 2000s.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/japanese-hardcore/">Japanese Hardcore</a>
                  <p>Bands from Japan, performing styles such as Burning Spirits, Crust Punk, and Thrashcore.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/japanese-hip-hop/">Japanese Hip Hop</a>
                  <p>Hip Hop which is created by artists who are either based in or from Japan.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/japanese-idol/">Japanese Idol</a>
                  <p>Contemporary Japanese singer-dancers valued mainly for their personality and charisma, often performing as groups in a cutesy and youthful style.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/alternative-idol/">Alternative Idol</a>
                  <p>Unconventional approaches characterized by alternative music styles and often unusual public images.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/j-core/">J-core</a>
                  <p>Eclectic scene of Japanese Hardcore [EDM] heavily associated with Doujin Music.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/future-core/">Future Core</a>
                  <p>Blends the speed, basslines, and rhythms of UK Hardcore (mostly coming from the J-core sphere) with euphoric, woozy synths, 7th chords and arpeggios, and vocal chops of Future Bass, particularly Kawaii Future Bass.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/jersey-shore-sound/">Jersey Shore Sound</a>
                  <p>Stylistically correlated to Heartland Rock, with cultural origins in coastal New Jersey; characterized by its horn-heavy mixture of 1960s Rock &amp; Roll, Rhythm &amp; Blues, and Doo-Wop.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/jovem-guarda/">Jovem Guarda</a>
                  <p>1960s Brazilian youth-oriented Pop Rock, with romantic lyrics and influenced by Merseybeat and Rockabilly.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/j-pop/">J-Pop</a>
                  <p>Commercial Pop of Japan after the advent of the Heisei era (1989), characterized by modernized production, a more eclectic sound palette, and a more westernized vocal style.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/akishibu-kei/">Akishibu-kei</a>
                  <p>Otaku inclined update of the style pioneered by the Shibuya-kei scene, mixed with J-Pop and often tied to Anime and Video Game Music.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/denpa/">Denpa</a>
                  <p>Underground style aiming to be bizarre yet catchy, using off-key and high-pitched vocals, strange or nonsensical lyrics, repetitive chants, onomatopoeia, frantic and "off-kilter" production, and "moe" aesthetics.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/wa-euro/">Wa Euro</a>
                  <p>Traditional form of J-Pop that emerged in the second half of the 1980s from late Hi-NRG, '80s British Dance-Pop and Italo-Disco/Eurobeat.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
