            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/mod/">Mod</a>
                  <p>1960s youth subculture in the United Kingdom, drawing from British Rhythm &amp; Blues, Beat, Garage Rock, and Pop sensibilities alongside a distinctive fashion style.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/mod-revival/">Mod Revival</a>
                  <p>Late 1970s and early 1980s revival of Mod fashion and music, featuring influence from the nascent Punk Rock scene.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/moscow-school/">Moscow School</a>
                  <p>School of Russian Western Classical Music composers centered on Moscow in the mid-to-late 19th century.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/motswako/">Motswako</a>
                  <p>Mainly rapped in a mixture of Setswana and English, incorporating additional languages and local South African and Botswanan influences, particularly Kwaito.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/movida-madrilena/">Movida madrileña</a>
                  <p>Countercultural scene developed in Madrid, Spain, in the late 1970s as a reflection of the newfound freedom after the end of the Franco’s dictatorship; mainly playing New Wave, Synthpop and Post-Punk.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/nardcore/">Nardcore</a>
                  <p>Hardcore Punk scene originating in Oxnard, California, in the early 1980s which often emphasizes speed, aggression, and technicality, and is heavily associated with the local southern California skateboarding culture and a D.I.Y. ethos.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/nederbeat/">Nederbeat</a>
                  <p>Dutch answer to the British Beat boom of the 1960s.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/neo-rave/">Neo Rave</a>
                  <p>Revives the sound of late-'90s, early 2000s Hard Dance genres and combines it with Hard Techno drums and structure.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/nerdcore-hip-hop/">Nerdcore Hip Hop</a>
                  <p>Themes touch on such nerd mainstays as science, computers, and science fiction.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/nerdcore-techno/">Nerdcore Techno</a>
                  <p>Stylistically diverse form of underground Japanese Electronic Dance Music utilizing energetic beats built around samples from pop and/or nerd culture.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/neue-deutsche-welle/">Neue Deutsche Welle</a>
                  <p>Eclectic German scene influenced by Synthpop and various styles of Punk, sometimes associated with Industrial.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/neue-volksmusik/">Neue Volksmusik</a>
                  <p>Emerged in the Southern German region from  in the 1980s onwards as a reaction to the conservatism of Alpine Folk Music scenes, combining the genre with outside sources and paired with a strong sense of irony and progressive political views.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/new-brunswick-basement-scene/">New Brunswick Basement Scene</a>
                  <p>Underground Punk Rock, Emo, and Indie Rock scene centred around Rutgers University in New Brunswick, New Jersey.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/new-direction/">New Direction</a>
                  <p>Late 19th – early 20th century school of Russian Orthodox liturgical music drawing on traditional forms of Orthodox liturgical chant.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/new-london-jazz/">New London Jazz</a>
                  <p>Contemporary and eclectic Jazz scene based in London, UK, that pulls from a variety of styles, including Spiritual Jazz, Afro-Jazz, and Jazz Fusion, and is often influenced by other genres such as Electronic, Dub, and Hip Hop.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/new-music/">New Music</a>
                  <p>Developed when Japanese Singer-Songwriters incorporated elements of Contemporary Folk and Pop Rock with Kayōkyoku songwriting.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/new-orleans-blues/">New Orleans Blues</a>
                  <p>Diverse scene in New Orleans since the beginning of the 20th century, commonly associated with a sound led by rollicking pianos with syncopated beats and backed by horns.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/new-partisans/">New Partisans</a>
                  <p>Short-lived movement in the mid-to-late 1980s in Sarajevo which attempted to synthesise Pop Rock with elements of Yugoslav Folk music and the ideals of the 1940s Yugoslav partisan movement.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/new-pop/">New Pop</a>
                  <p>British-centric movement of 1980s acts utilising Post-Punk ideals in a mainstream Pop context, characterised by cross-style experimentation and a strong focus on visual aesthetics.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/new-primitivism/">New Primitivism</a>
                  <p>Cross-media movement in Sarajevo, active primarily in the 1980s and inspired by Yugoslav New Wave and Yugoslav Punk.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/new-romantic/">New Romantic</a>
                  <p>UK cultural movement associated with the early 1980s and defined by a distinct, flamboyant fashion sense.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/new-tone/">New Tone</a>
                  <p>Musically and socio-politically progressive movement noted for combatting prejudices and mixing together different styles of music, such as Electronic, Hip Hop, or Emo.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/new-wave-of-new-wave/">New Wave of New Wave</a>
                  <p>Short-lived British New Wave and Punk Rock revival scene, active primarily around 1993-94 before being pushed out by the mass popularity of Britpop; often derided as a media construct.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/new-way-of-danish-fuck-you/">New Way of Danish Fuck You</a>
                  <p>Copenhagen underground scene active in the late 2000s and early 2010s, drawing on Post-Punk, Industrial, Noise, Hardcore Punk, and Black Metal and embracing a raw, lo-fi, cassette-based recording style and DIY ethos.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/new-weird-america/">New Weird America</a>
                  <p>Diverse movement that originated in the Northeastern United States during the late 1990s and 2000s which reshaped mid-20th century Contemporary Folk influences through a psychedelic and avant-garde approach.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/new-weird-finland/">New Weird Finland</a>
                  <p>Rose to prominence in the early 2000s, based around a collective of musicians living primarily in the Finnish cities of Tampere, Turku and Helsinki and with a sound primarily rooted in Psychedelia, particularly Psychedelic Folk and its subgenres Free Folk and Freak Folk.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/new-york-hardcore/">New York Hardcore</a>
                  <p>Hardcore Punk bands from New York City from the 1980s and onwards.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/new-york-school/">New York School</a>
                  <p>Circle of avant-garde composers based in 1950s New York, most well known for pioneering the use of chance as a method of composition.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/nola-sludge/">NOLA Sludge</a>
                  <p>New Orleans–based Louisiana Metal scene, commonly cited as the birthplace of Sludge Metal.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/northern-gothic/">Northern Gothic</a>
                  <p>Modern recontexualisation of Gothic music, influenced by the regional politics, culture and geography of post-industrial 21st-century Northern England.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/northern-soul/">Northern Soul</a>
                  <p>Soul popular in northern England in the late 1960s and early 1970s, consisting primarily of lesser-known American artists in the mid-1960s copying the Motown Sound.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/nova-srpska-scena/">Nova srpska scena</a>
                  <p>Serbian Alternative Rock scene subject to media interest in the '00s and early '10s; influenced by the Yugoslav New Wave and contemporary Indie Rock.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/nova-vanguarda-paulistana/">Nova vanguarda paulistana</a>
                  <p>Southeastern Brazilian scene that emerged in the late 2000s based on experimentation with Samba and MPB styles.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/novaya-scena/">Novaya scena</a>
                  <p>Diverse Ukrainian avant-garde scene which emerged in the late 1980s.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/novo-dub/">Novo Dub</a>
                  <p>Alternative Electronic scene incorporating various influences, predominant in France.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/no-wave/">No Wave</a>
                  <p>Underground, avant-garde, anti-art movement and music scene based in New York City around 1976-1980; commonly incorporates elements like dissonance, atonality, and stream-of-consciousness lyrics into various genres.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/nueva-cancion/">Nueva canción</a>
                  <p>Latin American (Nueva canción latinoamericana) and Spanish (Nueva canción española) movement during the 1960s and 1970s.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/nueva-cancion-espanola/">Nueva canción española</a>
                  <p>Arose in Spain in the 1960s, inspired in part by Nova cançó's reclaiming of Catalan regional identity, that spread across the country in regional variations.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/nueva-cancion-latinoamericana/">Nueva canción latinoamericana</a>
                  <p>Politically-charged messages associated with the rise of leftist social movements; striving for a renewal of traditional Latin and Hispanic American Folk Music expressions.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/nueva-cancion-chilena/">Nueva canción chilena</a>
                  <p>Socially conscious style that sought to recover traditional Chilean folk music and fuse it with the broader musical trends of Latin America.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/nueva-trova/">Nueva trova</a>
                  <p>Found inspiration in the 1950s Cuban Revolution and had the intention of introducing new musical ideas to the original Trova.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/nuevo-cancionero/">Nuevo Cancionero</a>
                  <p>Musical-literary movement in Argentina that aimed to reevaluate and reinvigorate "la música popular nativa" (native popular music) and to be the voice of poor and marginalized Argentines.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/nueva-escena-chilena/">Nueva escena chilena</a>
                  <p>Indie music scene encompassing artists from a wide range of genres and cities of Chile.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/nueva-ola/">Nueva ola</a>
                  <p>Latin American movement in the late 1950s and the 1960s incorporating assorted styles of Western popular music, primarily Rock &amp; Roll and Pop.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/nwobhm/">NWOBHM</a>
                  <p>Acronym for new wave of British Heavy Metal, which occurred in the late 1970s, taking some influence from Punk Rock.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/onkyo/">Onkyo</a>
                  <p>Exploration of the physical traits of sound rather than music as expression.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/opm/">OPM</a>
                  <p>Filipino ballads prominent in the 1970s to early 1980s, combining the sentimentality, lush arrangements and vocal techniques of Kundiman with the instrumentations and rhythms of Manila Sound and Soft Rock.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/paisley-underground/">Paisley Underground</a>
                  <p>Emerged in Los Angeles in the early 1980s, featuring the energy of Power Pop and New Wave adorned with retro Psychedelia.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/palm-desert-scene/">Palm Desert Scene</a>
                  <p>Originated during the 1990s in Palm Desert, California, based in classic Hard Rock, Psychedelic Rock and the Alternative Rock sounds of the era.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/pansy-craze/">Pansy Craze</a>
                  <p>Period of popularity and visibility of LGBT+ and drag performers in US cities from the late 1920s to mid-1930s.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/pecs-underground-scene/">Pécs Underground Scene</a>
                  <p>Politically countercultural arts scene emerging in the 1980s in Pécs, Hungary.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/pessoal-do-ceara/">Pessoal do Ceará</a>
                  <p>Cultural movement that emerged in the 1970s as artists from Ceará migrated to the cultural hubs of southeastern Brazil.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/pop-kreatif/">Pop Kreatif</a>
                  <p>Scene from Indonesia made popular in the 1970s-80s; commonly features lush melodies and progressive arrangements borrowed from modern styles of Jazz, Pop Rock and R&amp;B.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/pop-yeh-yeh/">Pop Yeh-Yeh</a>
                  <p>Blends Western Beat and Psychedelia styles with asli singing and melodies drawn from Malay Folk Music.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/positive-punk/">Positive Punk</a>
                  <p>Early goth scene in London that grew out of the&nbsp;Anarcho-Punk&nbsp;movement and promoted themes of virtue and mysticism; commonly features wailing vocals, screeching guitars, prominent basslines, and eclectic drum patterns.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/p-pop/">P-Pop</a>
                  <p>Commercialized style from the Philippines, which served as the successor of Manila Sound and OPM, featuring various contemporary Western influences and primarily sung in Tagalog and English.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/progg/">Progg</a>
                  <p>Swedish movement centred around left-wing politics; emerged in the late 1960s and declined by the late 1970s due to internal divisions and the changing political climate.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/psichedelia-occulta-italiana/">Psichedelia occulta italiana</a>
                  <p>Psychedelic scene from Italy with a distinctly brooding, dark atmosphere indebted to the country's media and a warped approach to Italian cultural memory.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/psychsploitation/">Psychsploitation</a>
                  <p>Short-lived genre seeking to capitalise on the popularity of Psychedelia in the 1960s, featuring quickly and cheaply recorded material played by session musicians and put out by budget labels.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/sitarsploitation/">Sitarsploitation</a>
                  <p>Variant of Exotica capitalising on the surge of Western interest in Indian music in the late 1960s; featured melodies played on the sitar (or instruments imitating it) atop Easy Listening accompaniment.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/q-pop/">Q-Pop</a>
                  <p>Glamorous, catchy pop scene that emerged in Kazakhstan in the 2010s, inspired by K-Pop.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/queercore/">Queercore</a>
                  <p>Movement mainly distinguished by its lyrical content expressing the viewpoints of the LGBTQ+ community, as well as promoting queer pride and unity.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/rabm/">RABM</a>
                  <p>Leftist movement related to Crust Punk that variably espouses Marxist, environmentalist, and anarchist views.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/red-dirt/">Red Dirt</a>
                  <p>Oklahoman and Texan acts descended from the Stillwater, Oklahoma independent Country scene of the 1980s.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/riot-grrrl/">Riot Grrrl</a>
                  <p>Underground feminist Punk movement originating in the United States in the early 1990s.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/road-rap/">Road Rap</a>
                  <p>Emerged in the mid 2000s from Brixton and Peckham featuring abrasive tones, prominent Grime influence, and lyrics depicting circumstances of street gang violence in the UK.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/rock-barrial/">Rock barrial</a>
                  <p>Argentinian scene that started in the 1990s, inspired by Rock &amp; Roll, Blues Rock, Roots Rock, and sometimes Hard Rock, directed to a national public and dismissing modern international trends, often featuring lyrics describing the life in low-income neighbourhoods.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/rock-in-opposition/">Rock in Opposition</a>
                  <p>Short-lived, international movement of ‘uncommercial’ Progressive Rock bands with left-wing politics; began its activity in early 1978 and faded out by the end of 1980, with 'reunion' festivals taking place from 2007 onwards.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/rock-kapak/">Rock Kapak</a>
                  <p>Melodic style blending elements of Malay Folk Music, such as lilting vocals, with influences from Heavy Metal and Glam Metal; commonly associated with power ballads referred to as rock jiwang.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/rock-radical-vasco/">Rock radical vasco</a>
                  <p>Punk music movement developed around 1983 by Basque Country and Navarre bands with a crude and abrasive sound and a 'radical' stance against the system, religion, the police and the 'Spanish State'.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/rock-sonico/">Rock sónico</a>
                  <p>Argentinian scene emerging in the early 1990s, influenced by Shoegaze, Noise Pop, Neo-Psychedelia, and sometimes Downtempo or Slacker Rock, defined by noisy, reverb-soaked guitars, introspective lyrics and lo-fi production.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/rock-subterraneo/">Rock subterráneo</a>
                  <p>Peruvian artistic and countercultural movement that emerged after the return to democracy in 1980, diversifying into various Punk styles between 1983 and 1992.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/rock-triste/">Rock triste</a>
                  <p>Brazilian Indie Rock movement popularized via the internet in mid 2010s commonly associated with styles such as Shoegaze, Midwest Emo, Dream Pop and relatives, iconic for its emphasis in melancholic and sad lyrics.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/rock-urbano-espanol/">Rock urbano español</a>
                  <p>Spanish scene originating in the mid-to-late 1970s that gained dominance with the end of the Francoist dictatorship and the end of censorship around lyrical topics like social issues.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/rock-urbano-mexicano/">Rock urbano mexicano</a>
                  <p>Scene born in the mid-to-late 1980s mainly in the marginal areas of Mexico City that took elements from Blues Rock, Hard Rock and Folk Rock.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/roman-school/">Roman School</a>
                  <p>Composers of primarily Christian Liturgical Music active in Rome in the 16th and 17th centuries, developing a musically conservative compositional style seen as appropriate for church performance.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/romanticism/">Romanticism</a>
                  <p>Expressive and emotional qualities, especially in terms of melody.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/grand-opera/">Grand opéra</a>
                  <p>French style characterized by its enlarged scope and sense of grandeur, with bigger orchestras and casts, and ornate sceneries and costumes.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/new-german-school/">New German School</a>
                  <p>Mid-19th-century Romantic movement experimenting in harmonics and form and engaged in social issues.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/romantische-oper/">Romantische Oper</a>
                  <p>Early 19th century Germanic style of Opera influenced by German Folk Music and legends with a focus on fantasy, emotivity, heroic figures, and nationalism.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/saint-petersburg-school/">Saint Petersburg School</a>
                  <p>Interrelated circles of 19th century Russian Western Classical Music composers focused on developing a distinctly Russian national style.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/russemusikk/">Russemusikk</a>
                  <p>Norwegian music crafted for the country's graduate celebrations known as russefeiring, typically features melodic, danceable, energetic production, and party-oriented, explicit singing and rapping.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/san-diego-sound/">San Diego Sound</a>
                  <p>Artistically diverse Punk and indie scene based around San Diego in the 1990s.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/san-francisco-sound/">San Francisco Sound</a>
                  <p>Influential Psychedelic Rock scene that developed out of Folk Rock in the mid 1960s; often emphasized atypical chord progressions and instrumental improvisation in the form of roving basslines and “cross-talking” guitars.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/haight-ashbury-scene/">Haight-Ashbury Scene</a>
                  <p>Influential Psychedelic Rock scene which emerged by summer 1966 in the Haight-Ashbury district of San Francisco and peaked in terms of notoriety by summer 1967, coinciding with a massive influx of visitors, media interest, and ensuing commercialisation.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/scene/">Scene</a>
                  <p>Youth subculture popularized in the 2000s via MySpace, spanning Metalcore, Pop Punk, Post-Hardcore, and related genres; associated with androgynous hairstyles, mall-sourced fashion, the Warped Tour festival circuit, and varied crossover with Electronic music.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/happy-rock/">Happy Rock</a>
                  <p>Late 2000s Brazilian movement made as a response against Emo with a bright aesthetic, heavy use of electronic instruments and distorted vocals.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/scottish-folk-revival/">Scottish Folk Revival</a>
                  <p>Revival of Scottish Folk Music which began around 1950 in Scotland and stagnated in the early 1970s.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/seapunk/">Seapunk</a>
                  <p>Short-lived early 2010s internet movement associated with oceanic imagery and computer graphics, deriving into vivid fashion trends, often incorporating aquatic elements into Electronic styles and visual aesthetics as well as influences by prominent tropes of 1990s rave culture.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/second-british-folk-revival/">Second British Folk Revival</a>
                  <p>Revival of Folk music in the United Kingdom which began at the end of the Second World War, peaked in the early-to-mid 1970s, and lost wider relevance by the end of the decade.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/second-viennese-school/">Second Viennese School</a>
                  <p>Influential circle of composers of very late Romanticism and Modern Classical who developed Expressionism and Serialism.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/second-wave-of-detroit-techno/">Second Wave of Detroit Techno</a>
                  <p>Transformative 1990s era of the Detroit Techno scene in Detroit, with harsher sounds and often militantly anti-corporate attitude.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/shibuya-kei/">Shibuya-kei</a>
                  <p>Eclectic scene emerging from the Shibuya district of Tokyo near the end of the 1980s; often borrows kitschy, retro-inspired aesthetics alongside diverse musical influences from Indie Pop, 1960s Pop and Easy Listening, Jazz, and Electronic styles.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/akishibu-kei/">Akishibu-kei</a>
                  <p>Otaku inclined update of the style pioneered by the Shibuya-kei scene, mixed with J-Pop and often tied to Anime and Video Game Music.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/picopop/">Picopop</a>
                  <p>Originated in the early 2000s as an offshoot of the Japanese Shibuya-kei movement when artists introduced more prominent "bleepy" electronic elements and faster tempos.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/shimokita-kei/">Shimokita-kei</a>
                  <p>Japanese style closely related to the Shimokitazawa indie scene, featuring Pop-informed songwriting, melodic guitar leads, expressive vocals, and often loud, prominent overdriven guitars.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/siberian-punk/">Siberian Punk</a>
                  <p>Emerged in the late 1980s, often blending the noisy, abrasive sound of Garage Punk and Post-Punk with radical anti-totalitarian lyrics drawing from British Punk influences.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/soundclown/">SoundClown</a>
                  <p>Scene focused on comedic, often ironic edits of pre-existing music, popular on SoundCloud in the mid-2010s.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/southern-hip-hop/">Southern Hip Hop</a>
                  <p>Hip Hop from artists based in the Southern region of the United States.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/south-florida-soundcloud-rap/">South Florida SoundCloud Rap</a>
                  <p>Mid-to-late 2010s Hip Hop scene noted for its use of internet platform SoundCloud to promote and distribute music, as well as lo-fi production and transgressive approaches to rapping.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/sovietwave/">Sovietwave</a>
                  <p>Scene of Synthwave that emerged in the early 2010s, taking its inspiration from Soviet Electronic electronic music and Soviet pop.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/straight-edge/">Straight Edge</a>
                  <p>Developed in the early 1980s D.C. Hardcore scene, promoting abstinence from the use of substances such as alcohol, tobacco, and other drugs.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/krishnacore/">Krishnacore</a>
                  <p>Straight Edge subculture that spawned from the New York Hardcore scene, promoting the Hare Krishna movement.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/vegan-straight-edge/">Vegan Straight Edge</a>
                  <p>Espouses veganism, environmentalism, and animal liberation causes.</p>
               </div>
         
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/h8000/">H8000</a>
                  <p>Belgian Hardcore [Punk] scene centered in West Flanders, famed for its Vegan Straight Edge Metalcore.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/hardline/">Hardline</a>
                  <p>Militant outgrowth of Vegan Straight Edge influenced by deep ecology.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/youth-crew/">Youth Crew</a>
                  <p>Hardcore Punk subculture that emerged in the mid-1980s New York Hardcore scene, distinguished by its optimistic and moralistic outlook and close ties to Straight Edge.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
         <ul class="hierarchy_list">
            <li class="hierarchy_list_item">
               <div class="hierarchy_list_item_details">
                  <a href="/genre/sunset-strip-glam-metal/">Sunset Strip Glam Metal</a>
                  <p>1980s Glam Metal scene based in West Hollywood, California, United States.</p>
               </div>
         
         
            </li>
         </ul>
                  
